other\nboot activities.  The original data is already present at boot and the\nfilesystem is not required until we are ready to start init.  It is\ntherefore reasonable to populate the rootfs asynchronously.  Move this\nprocessing to an async call.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second on a selection of test\nhardware particularly SMP systems, although UP system also benefit.\n\nSigned-off-by: Surbhi Palande <surbhi.palande@canonical.com>\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"5846f07dca1b309618c300e8062b2cb26158aa89","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/5846f07dca1b309618c300e8062b2cb26158aa89"},{"author":{"name":"Andy Whitcroft","email":"b4658fdd7fbd645c2859b0e39d71018f32058d12@canonical.com"},"message":"UBUNTU: SAUCE: isapnp_init: make isa PNP scans occur async\n\nThe results of scanning for devices is to trigger udev events therefore\nwe can push this processing async.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second x86 32bit systems.\n\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"66c8756f9a57e98aaa9d34429f49e01b5c4935eb","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/66c8756f9a57e98aaa9d34429f49e01b5c4935eb"}]},"repo":{"name":"jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci","id":2576692,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T00:30:55Z","id":"1508513611","type":"PushEvent"}

other\nboot activities. Move this\nprocessing to an async call.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second on a selection of test\nhardware particularly SMP systems, although UP system also benefit.\n\nSigned-off-by: Surbhi Palande <surbhi.palande@canonical.com>\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"3251ca2ea2cfb82a6f55e45b635a3b049fe1808e","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/3251ca2ea2cfb82a6f55e45b635a3b049fe1808e"},{"author":{"name":"Andy Whitcroft","email":"b4658fdd7fbd645c2859b0e39d71018f32058d12@canonical.com"},"message":"UBUNTU: SAUCE: isapnp_init: make isa PNP scans occur async\n\nThe results of scanning for devices is to trigger udev events therefore\nwe can push this processing async.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second x86 32bit systems.\n\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"a1fa616f640d96c0daedf01777564ca61f7f01e2","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/a1fa616f640d96c0daedf01777564ca61f7f01e2"}]},"repo":{"name":"jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci","id":2576692,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T00:43:37Z","id":"1508514206","type":"PushEvent"}

No problems there.\r\n\r\nCurrently, if you set \"warnononetimescriptchanges\" true, RH will report the altered script and continue running.  It will *not* attempt to  execute the updated script.\r\n\r\nThis patch changes that behavior so that if you set \"warnononetimescriptchanges\" true, RH reports script alteration, then runs the updated script and records the new script run information. various makefiles assume that $(obj)/whatever is\nexecutable on the build host.\n\nThis patch introduces a new variable called KBUILD_SCRIPTROOT\nthat points to script/binaries to use while cross compiling.\n\nUsage:\n\nBuild scripts for the build host:\n\tmake O=path/to/buildhost/buildscripts \\\n\t\tsilentoldconfig prepare scripts\nThen cross build script for target:\n\tmake O=path/to/target/buildscripts \\\n\t\tHOSTCC=$CROSS_COMPILE \\\n\t\tKBUILD_SCRIPTROOT=path/to/buildhost/buildscripts\n\t\tsilentoldconfig prepare scripts\n\nThis patch does not use KBUILD_SCRIPTROOT for all script invocations\nit only redefines the following if KBUILD_SCRIPTROOT is defined.\n\nscripts/Makefile.build\n\tscripts/basic/fixdep --> $(KBUILD_SCRIPTROOT)/scripts/basic/fixdep\n\nscripts/kconfig/Makefile\n\t$(obj)/conf --> $(KBUILD_SCRIPTROOT)/scripts/kconfig/conf\n\nscripts/mod/Makefile\n\t$(obj)mk_elfconfig --> The method \"test_ray\" is the main function.\r\n\r\nThanks\r\nRemo","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mrdoob/three.js/issues/932","labels":[{"color":"ffcfcf","name":"Bug","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mrdoob/three.js/labels/Bug"}],"number":932,"milestone":null,"updated_at":"2012-01-01T00:49:06Z","html_url":"https://github.com/mrdoob/three.js/issues/932","state":"open","id":2593939,"assignee":null,"user":{"avatar_url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/d8ddea8c595cf0ae9a3878d11103a520?d=https://a248.e.akamai.net/assets.github.com%2Fimages%2Fgravatars%2Fgravatar-140.png","id":804941,"login":"remoe","gravatar_id":"d8ddea8c595cf0ae9a3878d11103a520","url":"https://api.github.com/users/remoe"}},"action":"created","comment":{"updated_at":"2012-01-01T00:49:05Z","created_at":"2012-01-01T00:49:05Z","id":3323453,"body":"@mrdoob, your suspicion is correct.\r\n\r\nThere are two problems with the logic in `Ray.js`.\r\n\r\nThe first problem is the code in `intersectObject()` that eliminates an object from contention based on it's bounding sphere.\r\n\r\nYou can only eliminate an object if either:\r\n\r\n    (1) (the line defined by the ray fails to intersect the bounding sphere) OR\r\n\r\n    (2) (the sphere center is 'behind' the ray) AND (the ray origin is outside the sphere).\r\n\r\nThe code fails to check the second condition of (2), and erroneously eliminates objects that it shouldn't. You can't eliminate an object if the ray origin is inside the bounding sphere.\r\n\r\nThe second problem is the code in `intersectObject()` that eliminates an object's face by checking if the `face.centroid` is behind the ray origin. This test is also invalid. (Imagine standing slightly more than half-way down a long corridor -- the corridor's centroid is behind you, but there is still almost half the corridor in front of you.)\r\n\r\nHere is a fiddle that demonstrates the bug: http://jsfiddle.net/CJRTh/ . other\nboot activities.  The original data is already present at boot and the\nfilesystem is not required until we are ready to start init.  It is\ntherefore reasonable to populate the rootfs asynchronously. other\nboot activities.  The original data is already present at boot and the\nfilesystem is not required until we are ready to start init.  It is\ntherefore reasonable to populate the rootfs asynchronously.  Move this\nprocessing to an async call.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second on a selection of test\nhardware particularly SMP systems, although UP system also benefit.\n\nSigned-off-by: Surbhi Palande <surbhi.palande@canonical.com>\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"c56c06c5bd50fca9e729060dea1f1789f33422f2","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/c56c06c5bd50fca9e729060dea1f1789f33422f2"},{"author":{"name":"Andy Whitcroft","email":"b4658fdd7fbd645c2859b0e39d71018f32058d12@canonical.com"},"message":"UBUNTU: SAUCE: isapnp_init: make isa PNP scans occur async\n\nThe results of scanning for devices is to trigger udev events therefore\nwe can push this processing async.\n\nThis reduces kernel initialisation time (the time from bootloader to\nstarting userspace) by several 10ths of a second x86 32bit systems.\n\nSigned-off-by: Andy Whitcroft <apw@canonical.com>","sha":"10a5208a9f9463f0e28e2b13deace6924076c479","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci/commits/10a5208a9f9463f0e28e2b13deace6924076c479"}]},"repo":{"name":"jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci","id":2576692,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/jcrigby/packaged-linux-linaro-3.1-ci"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T00:58:08Z","id":"1508514827","type":"PushEvent"}

Later on, the typer will resolve \"s\"\nto be an extension macro for Quasiquote and will invoke that macro, which, in its turn,\nwill produce the glue that involves StringContext and Formatted as mentioned in the SID.\n\nStuff to do:\n1) \"splices\" field in Quasiquote should have type List[Ucode] (see comments in Quasiquote.scala)\n2) Escaping of string parts for string interpolation facility (can be done in Typers)\n3) Code quasiquoting provider (use typedUseCase to see how one can invoke parser from Typers)\n4) Pattern matching for code quasiquotes: implement functionality, complete the test","sha":"2cf50ce1196697914a773f8fc8166b73bd17b292","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/scalamacros/kepler/commits/2cf50ce1196697914a773f8fc8166b73bd17b292"}]},"repo":{"name":"scalamacros/kepler","id":2891159,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/scalamacros/kepler"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T01:00:10Z","id":"1508514909","type":"PushEvent"}

One is for thing like Builder and Publisher, where we get a lot of instances created and retained in a single JVM. This is `Descriptor` and `Describable` and we've already got a proven mechanism to define more wrappers.\r\n\r\nThe other kind, which is actually more fundamental, is a mechanism for Jenkins to discover singleton instances that are the extension points, such as `EnvironmentContributor`, `RunListener`, and `PageDecorator` (`Descriptor` is actually just one of these, and `Describable` is just a further layer above.)\r\n\r\nThis pull request adds a mechanism for us to rapidly define such singleton extension points.\r\n\r\nThe main change is the `ExtensionPoint` module, which is a mix-in that detects subtype implementations, and it'll invoke a callback specified via the `when_implemented` class method. I've added a couple of actual wrappers based on this mechanism (and used them successfuly in the RVM plugin.)\r\n\r\nOne thing that I couldn't quite figure out was how to modify `Jenkins::Model::Describable` to use `ExtensionPoint` to avoid dupliation of the subtype detection logic. Ford","email":"1ea48a69f09ca4fa2c0ea576825eb76dcaab3f18@gmail.com"},"message":"Removed CharArray. Use ByteArray in String.\n\nInitially, the thought was that a CharArray could encapsulate the idea of a\nvector of bytes and the interpretation of those bytes relative to a particular\nencoding scheme. However, in practice, the interpretation of those bytes is\nreally encapsulated in String, which composes a ByteArray and an Encoding.\nPushing the logic down into CharArray required delegating almost everything\nfrom String, which is a good indicator for a poor abstraction.\n\nOne example in particular illustrates this: a ByteArray (and CharArray)\ncontain a boundary-aligned number of bytes, the boundary being a machine word.\nThe size of a ByteArray (CharArray) is always >= to the number of bytes needed\nfor a String's data. Encoding operations need to operate on the precise number\nof bytes in the String's data because those extra bytes that pad to a boundary\nin a ByteArray would be misinterpreted in some Encodings.\n\nEssentially, the more Encoding-aware CharArray became, the more it was just a\nString under String. The first thing the subroutine\ndid was GetMarcBiblio, and the $biblionumber passed was never used again.\n\nThis subroutine was only used 3 places: opac/opac-search.pl, opac/opac-detail.pl,\nand C4/VirtualShelves/Page.pm.  In the first and last cases, it was used in a loop.\nIn the last two cases, a call to GetMarcBiblio had already been done.  This is expensive, and\nwe were doing it twice per record.\n\nFor opac/opac-search.pl, the call to GetMarcBiblio was moved to just outside GetCOinSBiblio;\nthis will not change the performance at all. (This comes from an [unintentional] additional\nupdate statement in DelItem.) It makes deletion time visible.\nIn the past, the marcxml was updated too at that moment, resulting in an\nupdated timestamp in biblioitems too. The first thing the subroutine\ndid was GetMarcBiblio, and the $biblionumber passed was never used again.\n\nThis subroutine was only used 3 places: opac/opac-search.pl, opac/opac-detail.pl,\nand C4/VirtualShelves/Page.pm. This is expensive, and\nwe were doing it twice per record.\n\nFor opac/opac-search.pl, the call to GetMarcBiblio was moved to just outside GetCOinSBiblio;\nthis will not change the performance at all. One is for thing like Builder and Publisher, where we get a lot of instances created and retained in a single JVM. This is `Descriptor` and `Describable` and we've already got a proven mechanism to define more wrappers.\r\n\r\nThe other kind, which is actually more fundamental, is a mechanism for Jenkins to discover singleton instances that are the extension points, such as `EnvironmentContributor`, `RunListener`, and `PageDecorator` (`Descriptor` is actually just one of these, and `Describable` is just a further layer above.)\r\n\r\nThis pull request adds a mechanism for us to rapidly define such singleton extension points.\r\n\r\nThe main change is the `ExtensionPoint` module, which is a mix-in that detects subtype implementations, and it'll invoke a callback specified via the `when_implemented` class method. {"actor":{"avatar_url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/3b668c42c7f806dcde0448819586ccfd?d=http://github.dev%2Fimages%2Fgravatars%2Fgravatar-user-420.png","id":355239,"login":"gegerlan","gravatar_id":"3b668c42c7f806dcde0448819586ccfd","url":"https://api.github.dev/users/gegerlan"},"public":true,"payload":{"head":"f4d3ae6485f5e9ab7e8d9460bcdf1988cfd9f842","ref":"refs/heads/raise_history","size":1,"push_id":55758607,"commits":[{"author":{"name":"gegerlan","email":"dcaf86e880df014effec6ad89c7ec635f0d3cfbb@hotmail.com"},"message":"Added raise to Game_Interpreter and history to raise.\n\nHistory allows for tracking when changes are done to attributes. This can be used for capturing repeatable (and exploitable) events, or if you want to have the impact of changes vary over time (e.g. each change can have a different impact on the attribute based on how long ago it happened).\n\nGame_Troop\n  setup_battle_event - will now pass the page for events played out\n\nGame_Event\n:page_id\n  The current page of the event. This is made available for the Game_Interpreter to read, but will also be passed to the interpreter when the event autoruns.\n\nGame_Interpreter\n@page_id\n  The current page number of the event being run\n:raise(attribute, amount, max[, custom_context])\n  Retrieves the context (map_id, event_id, page_id) + passed custom_context, and passes it on to the player's :raise method. Player is considered the leader of the game_party.\n  Can be called using the script event command.\n\n    raise(\"pervert\", 1, 50) # add 1 to perversion, up to 50\n    raise(\"pervert\", 3, 60, \"mySpecialContext\") # add 3 to perversion, up to 60, for context \"mySpecialContext\"\n\nGame_actor\n:raise(attribute, amount, max[, context])\n  context - value that uniquely identifies the attribute raise.\n  If there's a history of the context used for raising the attribute before, it will lessen the change by the number of times called (2 times = delta / 2, 3 times = delta/3 and so on) until the it reaches 1, which will change the delta to 0.\n:attribute_history\n  ... is a hash containing changes through raise. Key is the context [map_id, event_id, page_id], and the value is when it happened in game time (in seconds).\n\nIndex (where on the page the script call is) is not used by default for\nthe context, since it may give you faulty result during development (where\nthe page position of the command may change). If it's known that the event's won't change, then having it would be better, because it wouldn't interfere in those cases where one page can do a number of changes to the same attribute (and you don't want to lose context). A workaround is to add a custom context by e.g. adding a digit.\n\n    def wear_plugged_tail(do_wear) # script command on an event's page\n      if do_wear\n        raise(\"pervert\", 5, 50, 1) # Add 5, up to 50, for context 1\n      else\n        raise(\"pervert\", 3, 50, 2) # Add 5, up to 50, for context 2\n      end\n    end\n\n    actor.pervert = 0\n    wear_plugged_tail(false) # don't wear\n      => 3 # pervert raised by 3 = 3 / 1\n    wear_plugged_tail(true) # do wear\n      => 8 # pervert raised by 5 = 5 / 1\n    wear_plugged_tail(true) # do wear\n      => 10 # pervert raised by 2 = 5 / 2\n\nThe extra context will only extend the existing contest (map, event, page)\nso it can only be used to (un)link raise commands on a page.","sha":"f4d3ae6485f5e9ab7e8d9460bcdf1988cfd9f842","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gegerlan/Gentle-Love-Quest/commits/f4d3ae6485f5e9ab7e8d9460bcdf1988cfd9f842"}]},"repo":{"name":"gegerlan/Gentle-Love-Quest","id":3059528,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/gegerlan/Gentle-Love-Quest"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T01:31:02Z","id":"1508516153","type":"PushEvent"}

Later on, the typer will resolve \"s\"\nto be an extension macro for Quasiquote and will invoke that macro, which, in its turn,\nwill produce the glue that involves StringContext and Formatted as mentioned in the SID.\n\nStuff to do:\n1) \"splices\" field in Quasiquote should have type List[Ucode] (see comments in Quasiquote.scala)\n2) Escaping of string parts for string interpolation facility (can be done in Typers)\n3) Code quasiquoting provider (use typedUseCase to see how one can invoke parser from Typers)\n4) Pattern matching for code quasiquotes: implement functionality, complete the test","sha":"5fbe205187a8da84490ec6b6e787f9bd573f7f74","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/scalamacros/kepler/commits/5fbe205187a8da84490ec6b6e787f9bd573f7f74"}]},"repo":{"name":"scalamacros/kepler","id":2891159,"url":"https://api.github.dev/repos/scalamacros/kepler"},"created_at":"2012-01-01T01:31:42Z","id":"1508516172","type":"PushEvent"}

|reportFailures| variable.\nSo far it was a boolean and its value was saved before changing and\nrestored afterwards (requiring additional variable in few places). This\npatch changes it to an integer where value 0 means \"report errors\" and\nanything > 0 means \"do not report errors\".  Instead of saving/restoring\nwe can now simple increment/decrement (avoiding the additional\nvariable and simplifying the code).\n\nThis change speeds up the benchmark suite execution by 0.66%.\n\nDetailed results (benchmark suite totals as reported by \"jake benchmark\"\non Node.js 0.4.8):\n\n-----------------------------------\n Test #      Before        After\n-----------------------------------\n      1   129.26 kB/s   128.28 kB/s\n      2   127.34 kB/s   127.53 kB/s\n      3   126.72 kB/s   129.01 kB/s\n      4   126.89 kB/s   128.05 kB/s\n      5   126.46 kB/s   127.98 kB/s\n-----------------------------------\nAverage   127.33 kB/s   128.17 kB/s\n-----------------------------------","sha":"bb83b2189a77db570ea6f846f513a2c6b8918fb1","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stonecobra/pegjs/commits/bb83b2189a77db570ea6f846f513a2c6b8918fb1"},{"author":{"name":"David Majda","email":"aa743a0aaec8f7d7a1f01442503957f4d7a2d634@majda.cz"},"message":"Rewrite variable handling in generated parsers\n\nBefore this commit, variables for saving match results and parse\npositions in generated parsers were not used efficiently. Each rule\nbasically used its own variable(s) for storing the data, with names\ngenerated sequentially during code emitting. There was no reuse of\nvariables and a lot of unnecessary assignments between them.\n\nIt is easy to see that both match results and parse positions can\nactually be stored on a stack that grows as the parser walks deeper in\nthe grammar tree and shrinks as it returns. Moreover, if one creates a\nnew stack for each rule the parser enters, its maximum depth can be\ncomputed statically from the grammar. This allows us to implement the\nstack not as an array, but as a set of numbered variables in each\nfunction that handles parsing of a grammar rule, avoiding potentially\nslow array accesses.\n\nThis commit implements the idea from the previous paragraph, using\nseparate stack for match results and for parse positions. As a result,\ndefined variables are reused and unnecessary copying avoided.\n\nSpeed implications\n------------------\n\nThis change speeds up the benchmark suite execution by 2.14%.\n\nDetailed results (benchmark suite totals as reported by \"jake benchmark\"\non Node.js 0.4.8):\n\n-----------------------------------\n Test #      Before        After\n-----------------------------------\n      1   129.01 kB/s   131.98 kB/s\n      2   129.39 kB/s   130.13 kB/s\n      3   128.63 kB/s   132.57 kB/s\n      4   127.53 kB/s   129.82 kB/s\n      5   127.98 kB/s   131.80 kB/s\n-----------------------------------\nAverage   128.51 kB/s   131.26 kB/s\n-----------------------------------\n\nSize implications\n-----------------\n\nThis change makes a sample of generated parsers 8.60% smaller:\n\nBefore:\n\n  $ wc -c src/parser.js examples/*.js\n   110867 src/parser.js\n    13886 examples/arithmetics.js\n   450125 examples/css.js\n   632390 examples/javascript.js\n    61365 examples/json.js\n  1268633 total\n\nAfter:\n\n  $ wc -c src/parser.js examples/*.js\n    99597 src/parser.js\n    13077 examples/arithmetics.js\n   399893 examples/css.js\n   592044 examples/javascript.js\n    54797 examples/json.js\n  1159408 total","sha":"d123cf0eda1a459d9e6c662c45b40de639196207","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stonecobra/pegjs/commits/d123cf0eda1a459d9e6c662c45b40de639196207"},{"author":{"name":"David Majda","email":"aa743a0aaec8f7d7a1f01442503957f4d7a2d634@majda.cz"},"message":"Add /tools/impact script to measure speed and size impact of commits","sha":"d0c96481bfdd43178554829e1dcd7916cc581b06","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stonecobra/pegjs/commits/d0c96481bfdd43178554829e1dcd7916cc581b06"},{"author":{"name":"David Majda","email":"aa743a0aaec8f7d7a1f01442503957f4d7a2d634@majda.cz"},"message":"Make /tools/improve script measure speed 5 times and compute an average\n\nI measured speed 5 times manually too before introducing the script. We don't want users to hold such devices\ncaptive or cause system problems by fencing them off into an iommu\ndomain.  We determine \"permission to use\" by testing whether the user\nhas access to the PCI sysfs resource files. instead report it to userspace.\nBecause the feature depends on KVM_CREATE_IRQCHIP, which we cannot guarantee\nwill be called, we expose it via a KVM_CAP_TSC_DEADLINE_TIMER and not\nKVM_GET_SUPPORTED_CPUID.\n\nFixes the Illumos guest kernel, which uses the TSC deadline timer feature.\n\n[avi: add the KVM_CAP + documentation]\n\nReported-by: Alexey Zaytsev <alexey.zaytsev@gmail.com>\nTested-by: Alexey Zaytsev <alexey.zaytsev@gmail.com>\nSigned-off-by: Jan Kiszka <jan.kiszka@siemens.com>\nSigned-off-by: Avi Kivity <avi@redhat.com>","sha":"4d25a066b69fb749a39d0d4c610689dd765a0b0e","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iflema/linux/commits/4d25a066b69fb749a39d0d4c610689dd765a0b0e"},{"author":{"name":"Andreas Schwab","email":"c9df6394cb541f693236245820fbe23866f1a3fe@linux-m68k.org"},"message":"KVM: PPC: move compute_tlbie_rb to book3s_64 common header\n\ncompute_tlbie_rb is only used on ppc64 and cannot be compiled on ppc32.\n\nSigned-off-by: Andreas Schwab <schwab@linux-m68k.org>\nSigned-off-by: Alexander Graf <agraf@suse.de>","sha":"36cc66d638d3ffbc635b0d48b29c1128fdad38f4","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iflema/linux/commits/36cc66d638d3ffbc635b0d48b29c1128fdad38f4"},{"author":{"name":"Andreas Schwab","email":"c9df6394cb541f693236245820fbe23866f1a3fe@linux-m68k.org"},"message":"KVM: PPC: protect use of kvmppc_h_pr\n\nkvmppc_h_pr is only available if CONFIG_KVM_BOOK3S_64_PR.\n\nSigned-off-by: Andreas Schwab <schwab@linux-m68k.org>\nSigned-off-by: Alexander Graf <agraf@suse.de>","sha":"96f38d72867bc54c312decaf8463f1e9607136da","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/iflema/linux/commits/96f38d72867bc54c312decaf8463f1e9607136da"},{"author":{"name":"Michael Neuling","email":"7b0ab45a730e48a69239010b5b8fe5fa4e8eaac6@neuling.org"},"message":"KVM: PPC: fix kvmppc_start_thread() for CONFIG_SMP=N\n\nCurrently kvmppc_start_thread() tries to wake other SMT threads via\nxics_wake_cpu(). 778fc546f749 (\"locks: fix tracking of\ninprogress lease breaks\") introduced a possible error pointer\ndereference on failure to allocate memory.  locks_conflict() will\ndereference the passed-in new The current implementation of these is very inefficient because it recalculates all permissions of a Permissible whenever a single permission of the attachment changes (sometimes even if nothing changes at all). Especially when there are thousands of permissions registered on the server, it may take up to several seconds if a lot of single permissions have to be added to an permission attachment.\r\n\r\nThis commit will highly improve performance and allow to add/remove multiple permissions at once. I've got a little byte code post processor to inject synthetic bridge methods to help me evolve code without breaking existing binaries, (http://bridge-method-injector.infradna.com/), and as a part of this I generate a bridge method whose return type is narrower, instead of wider.\r\n\r\nThat is, whereas normally bridge methods are as follows:\r\n<pre>\r\ninterface Base {\r\n    Object foo();\r\n}\r\n\r\nclass Impl implements Base {\r\n    String foo() {...}\r\n\r\n    // the above definition causes javac to insert the following\r\n    // bridge method\r\n    @Synthetic @Bridge\r\n    Object foo() { return <String>foo(); }\r\n}\r\n<\/pre>\r\n\r\nmy byte code post processing would produce this:\r\n\r\n```\r\nclass Impl /* no interface needed */ {\r\n    Object foo() {...}\r\n\r\n    @Synthetic @Bridge\r\n    String foo() { return (String)<Object>foo(); }\r\n}\r\n```\r\nThis works with javac, in the sense that it'll invoke \"Object foo()\", by preferring non-bridge methods for resolution.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, JRuby doesn't discreminate against bridge methods, so it can end up calling \"String foo()\" depending on the exact implementation detail of the search.\r\n\r\nThis fix eliminates this issue by making JRuby ignore all bridge methods. Would you please please include this?\r\n\r\n(In the past I've made [a similar patch to Groovy](http://jira.codehaus.org/browse/GROOVY-5003))","head":{"ref":"bridge","repo":{"forks":0,"owner":{"avatar_url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/0cb9832a01c22c083390f3c5dcb64105?d=https://a248.e.akamai.net/assets.github.com%2Fimages%2Fgravatars%2Fgravatar-140.png","id":50003,"login":"kohsuke","gravatar_id":"0cb9832a01c22c083390f3c5dcb64105","url":"https://api.github.com/users/kohsuke"},"private":false,"pushed_at":"2012-01-01T01:45:38Z","ssh_url":"git@github.com:kohsuke/jruby.git","created_at":"2011-07-01T18:10:32Z","watchers":1,"description":"JRuby, {"actor":{"avatar_url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9de0d6ad8a2215dd5fe3da79232d8c12?d=http://github.dev%2Fimages%2Fgravatars%2Fgravatar-user-420.png","id":322097,"login":"ZyX-I","gravatar_id":"9de0d6ad8a2215dd5fe3da79232d8c12","url":"https://api.github.dev/users/ZyX-I"},"public":true,"payload":{"issue":{"pull_request":{"patch_url":null,"html_url":null,"diff_url":null},"closed_at":null,"comments":8,"created_at":"2011-11-15T17:08:36Z","title":"Problems of {plugin}[{snr}] naming scheme","body":"I just realized that this scheme contains at least three problems:\r\n\r\n1. Addition of new plugin (renaming some of old plugins) with name matching old one will leave old plugin without updates.\r\n2. Renaming of some plugin will leave existing installations being not updated automatically anymore.\r\n3. You can make user update plugin with `name={plugin1}{snr1}` with plugin with `name={plugin2}={plugin1}{snr1}` if `{snr2}<{snr1}` (opposite leads to garbage names (`{plugin}{snr}{snr}`)).\r\n\r\nDo you have some statistics about how often does this happen and whether it is worth working on (first two, third is vulnerability and must be fixed)? I suggest\r\n\r\n1. Duplicating of just `{plugin}` entries with `{plugin}%{snr}` (easy), so one can always use persistent name.\r\n2. Having a renames file which will create warnings if you try to update renamed plugin.\r\n3. Replacing `{plugin}{snr}` scheme with `{plugin}%{snr}` as percent sign is not allowed to be in plugin names, but allowed in file names on windows (easy, but breaks compatibility). Another solution is to make script check whether newly created names is already taken, but this leads to garbage names (names with duplicate `{snr}` parts) as well.","url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MarcWeber/vim-addon-manager-known-repositories/issues/18","labels":[],"number":18,"milestone":null,"updated_at":"2012-01-01T01:51:37Z","html_url":"https://github.com/MarcWeber/vim-addon-manager-known-repositories/issues/18","state":"open","id":2246472,"assignee":null,"user":{"avatar_url":"https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/9de0d6ad8a2215dd5fe3da79232d8c12?d=https://a248.e.akamai.net/assets.github.com%2Fimages%2Fgravatars%2Fgravatar-140.png","id":322097,"login":"ZyX-I","gravatar_id":"9de0d6ad8a2215dd5fe3da79232d8c12","url":"https://api.github.com/users/ZyX-I"}},"action":"created","comment":{"updated_at":"2012-01-01T01:51:37Z","created_at":"2012-01-01T01:51:37Z","id":3323559,"body":"It may be better if users would be able to pass names `{name}%{snr}` or `%{snr}`: first to force check on matching script number and second to select plugin by its script number as it is the only persistent property of the plugin. Per cent sign will thus be reserved and forbidden in plugin names, but it is not a loss as it is not currently used. For plugins not posted on vim.org this is `{name}%{URL}`/`%{URL}`. It will prevent downloading plugins from untrusted source in cases like \u201cauthor renamed plugin and then bad guy created malware plugin named identical to old normal plugin name\u201d.\r\n\r\n// By the way, what should be used instead of \u201cbad guy\u201d here?
